  "body": "#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: `1.9.25`\r\nOS & Version: Linux\r\nCommit hash : (if `develop`)\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\ntransactions should be transmitted and acknowledged\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\ntransactions remain pending\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n1. create more than 1 node in a private network that uses the clique protocol\r\n2. make at least one node mine\r\n3. leave at least one node as a non-miner\r\n4. try sendTransaction from a non-mining node\r\n\r\n#### Backtrace\r\n\r\n````\r\n[backtrace]\r\n````\r\n\r\nAt least 3 issues have been reported and closed for this problem, and yet the problem remains, as far as I can tell, in geth 1.9.25.\r\nhttps://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/issues/2769\r\nhttps://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/issues/2980\r\nhttps://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/issues/3694\r\n\r\nI created a private network that uses the clique protocol.\r\nThe first node is designated as a signer in the genesis json. That node by itself worked fine.\r\n\r\nI created a second node. It syncs correctly but could not, at first, sendTransaction.\r\nI followed a workaround mentioned in the earlier issues: established mining on the second node.\r\nNow that works.\r\n\r\nI created a third node. it syncs correctly, but can not sendTransaction.\r\n\r\nWhat am I supposed to do? I don't want every node in my network to be a signer-sealer.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
